You can leverage [NavigableMap][1] interface that may be accessed and traversed in either ascending or descending key order. This interface is [intended to supersede][2] the SortedMap interface. The Navigable map is usually sorted according to the natural ordering of its keys, or by a Comparator provided at map creation time.

There are three most useful implementations of it: [TreeMap][3], [ImmutableSortedMap][4], and [ConcurrentSkipListMap][5]. 

TreeMap example:

    TreeMap&lt;String, Integer&gt; users = new TreeMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();
    users.put(&quot;Bob&quot;, 1);
    users.put(&quot;Alice&quot;, 2);
    users.put(&quot;John&quot;, 3);
   
    for (String key: users.keySet()) {
      System.out.println(key + &quot; (ID = &quot;+ users.get(key) + &quot;)&quot;);
    }

Output:

    Alice (ID = 2)
    Bob (ID = 1)
    John (ID = 3)

  [1]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/NavigableMap.html
  [2]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/technotes/guides/collections/changes6.html
  [3]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/TreeMap.html
  [4]: http://docs.guava-libraries.googlecode.com/git/javadoc/com/google/common/collect/ImmutableSortedMap.html
  [5]: http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ConcurrentSkipListMap.html

